What protein families do the interactors belong to?

Experimental pull down data represented on a volcano plot can be overlaid with information on protein families of enriched genes based on user defined significance. This analysis identifies protein families present in the uploaded proteomics data and can assist in functional annotation and exploration of diversity of protein function in the proteomics experiment.

Protein families present in proteomics data can be visualized as 1) volcano plot in the “ProteinFam: VP” tab and 2) scatter plot in the “ProteinFam: SP” tab.

Protein family lists are taken from the HGNC database which is curated by the HGNC appointed team.


Protein families as volcano plot



When marker sizing is turned on, the size of squares represent the number of respective protein families. Hovering over the marker will display protein encoded by gene in HGNC symbol, its protein family, and number of other proteins with the same protein family in user defined region.

Marker sizing can be turned off for equally sized markers. Any time user edits the input values, user must click on Generate Plot button to see the changes.

1. Marker sizing on

2. Marker sizing off




Protein families as scatter plot

This scatter plot is only applicable if the uploaded proteomics data contains two replicates (rep1 and rep2).

Visualizaing protein families present as a scatter plot is especially useful when identifying general outliers and background contaminants, for example, proteins that interact with affinity reagent or epitope tag. These outliers and contaminants often have poor correlation between two replicates and are plotted outside of the diagonal (shown in figure below).



One method to troubleshoot and identify background contaminants from bona fide interactors is to identify which protein families the outliers belong to.
